---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'CollectionPage',
  name: 'AI RPG Tools',
  description: 'Free browser-based tools for AI roleplay — platform comparison matrix, campaign memory trackers, and utilities for running coherent long-form AI RPG campaigns in ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini.',
  url: 'https://arcanumrpgs.com/tools',
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: 'Rukka', url: 'https://arcanumrpgs.com/about' },
};
---
<Base
  title="AI RPG Tools — Platform Comparison, Campaign Memory & More | Arcanum"
  description="Free browser-based AI RPG tools: compare all 10 reviewed roleplay platforms side by side, track campaign memory, generate compression prompts, and keep your ChatGPT, Claude, or Gemini campaign coherent."
  type="website"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <div class="wrap tools-page">

    <p class="eyebrow mono">// tools</p>
    <h1>AI RPG Tools</h1>

    <div class="intro prose">
      <p>Two problems define AI roleplay: choosing the right platform to begin with, and keeping your campaign coherent once you're running. These tools address both — one at the start of the journey, one deep inside it. No accounts. No data sent anywhere. Everything runs in your browser.</p>
      <p>Built by <a href="/about">Rukka</a> — four decades across tabletop RPGs, CRPGs, MMOs, and AI-driven roleplay systems — these tools come out of the same thinking behind the <a href="/arcanum-games">Arcanum Originals</a>: that a long AI campaign isn't luck, it's architecture. The right structure makes the difference between a story that holds together and one that quietly falls apart by session four.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tools-grid">

      <div class="tool-card">
        <div class="tool-card-inner">
          <div class="tool-tag mono">Memory &amp; Context</div>
          <h2>Campaign Memory Tool</h2>
          <p class="tool-desc">Around turn 50, AI campaigns hit a wall: the model starts losing coherence as older messages scroll out of context. This is the <a href="/blog/why-llms-forget">turn-50 amnesia problem</a> — the most common failure in long AI roleplay — and this tool gives you a structured place to fight it. Log everything that matters: characters, plot threads, locations, relationships, inventory, world facts, and a last-scene anchor.</p>
          <p class="tool-desc">When the context gets heavy, hit <strong>Generate Compression Prompt</strong>. The tool outputs a briefing you paste into ChatGPT, Claude, or Gemini. The AI reads your full campaign state and returns a compact memory block — under 500 words — that you paste at the start of every new session to restore full context. Your data saves to a <code>.arcanum</code> file on your device; nothing is sent to any server.</p>
          <div class="tool-meta mono">
            <span class="badge">Free</span>
            <span class="badge">Client-side only</span>
            <span class="badge">Works with any AI</span>
          </div>
          <a class="tool-cta mono" href="/tools/campaign-memory">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tool-card">
        <div class="tool-card-inner">
          <div class="tool-tag mono">Session Setup</div>
          <h2>AI RPG Prompt Builder</h2>
          <p class="tool-desc">The gap between "I want to run an RPG in ChatGPT" and a session that actually holds together is almost always the system prompt. This tool builds one in under a minute: select your model, genre, tone, focus, and campaign length, and it assembles a structured, copy-paste-ready system prompt — no AI called, no account needed, runs entirely in your browser.</p>
          <p class="tool-desc">Drop the result into ChatGPT as Custom GPT instructions, a Claude Project's custom instructions, or a Gemini Gem. The prompt establishes genre, tone, agency rules, and memory continuity from turn one. Use the <strong>Long Campaign</strong> option to append save-state and compression instructions that pair directly with the Campaign Memory Tool.</p>
          <div class="tool-meta mono">
            <span class="badge">Free</span>
            <span class="badge">Client-side only</span>
            <span class="badge">ChatGPT · Claude · Gemini</span>
          </div>
          <a class="tool-cta mono" href="/tools/prompt-builder">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tool-card">
        <div class="tool-card-inner">
          <div class="tool-tag mono">Research &amp; Discovery</div>
          <h2>Platform Comparison Matrix</h2>
          <p class="tool-desc">Ten reviewed AI roleplay platforms — <a href="/clients/friends-and-fables">Friends & Fables</a>, <a href="/clients/roleforge">RoleForge</a>, <a href="/clients/janitor">Janitor AI</a>, and seven more — in a single sortable table. The columns that matter most: rating, pricing tier, which AI models run under the hood, and how each platform handles memory across sessions.</p>
          <p class="tool-desc">Filter by free or freemium. Sort by rating or platform name. Click through to the full review for any entry. The <strong>Memory</strong> column alone tells you which platforms can sustain a six-month campaign and which ones degrade by session four — that distinction is harder to find anywhere else.</p>
          <div class="tool-meta mono">
            <span class="badge">Free</span>
            <span class="badge">10 platforms</span>
            <span class="badge">Sortable &amp; filterable</span>
          </div>
          <a class="tool-cta mono" href="/clients/compare">Open tool →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="closing prose">
      <h2>Why These Tools Exist Separately from the Games</h2>
      <p>The <a href="/tools/prompt-builder">AI RPG Prompt Builder</a> is for the question before the first turn: how do I give the AI the instructions it needs to actually run a game? A well-structured system prompt defines genre, tone, agency rules, and memory continuity before the player types a single word — it is the difference between a session that holds together and one that quietly improvises its way off the rails by turn ten.</p>
      <p>The comparison matrix is for the question before the campaign starts: which platform is actually worth your time? It pulls every reviewed client into one place so you can make that call without opening ten tabs — and points directly into the full write-up when you need the reasoning behind a rating.</p>
      <p>The Campaign Memory Tool is for the question that arrives around session four: why does the AI keep losing the thread? Context windows fill. Models drift. Characters forget what happened ten scenes ago. The tool gives you a structured place to fight that — state logging, a compression prompt, a <code>.arcanum</code> file that saves to your device.</p>
      <p>The <a href="/arcanum-games">Arcanum Originals</a> — Aevum, Eirathis, The Chronicler, Star Freighter Drift — solve the memory problem from the inside, with compression and state management built into the system prompt itself. If you download one of those games, you don't need the Campaign Memory Tool. But for homebrew campaigns running in any model, on any platform — these tools bring the same structural discipline without requiring you to change how you play.</p>
      <p>If you haven't read <a href="/blog/why-llms-forget">why AI campaigns fall apart at turn 50</a>, that article is the technical foundation behind both the memory tool and the Originals. Understanding the context window problem — and the specific fixes that work — makes everything here more effective.</p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <style>
    .tools-page { padding: 3rem 1.25rem 5rem; }
    .eyebrow { color: var(--rune); font-size: .78rem; letter-spacing: .06em; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    h1 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1.6rem; }

    .intro.prose { max-width: 780px; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
    .intro.prose p { color: var(--parchment-dim); line-height: 1.85; font-size: 1.05rem; margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
    .intro.prose p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

    .tools-grid { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.2rem; max-width: 780px; margin-bottom: 3.5rem; }

    .tool-card {
      display: block;
      border: 1px solid var(--line);
      border-radius: 10px;
      background: var(--ink-2);
      color: var(--parchment);
      text-decoration: none;
      transition: border-color .18s;
    }
    .tool-card:hover { border-color: var(--ember); text-decoration: none; }
    .tool-card-inner { padding: 1.8rem 2rem; }
    .tool-tag { font-size: .7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .08em; color: var(--rune); margin-bottom: .7rem; }
    .tool-card h2 { font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: .8rem; color: var(--parchment); }
    .tool-desc { color: var(--parchment-dim); font-size: .97rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: .9rem; }
    .tool-desc a { color: var(--ember); }
    .tool-desc code { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: .84em; color: var(--rune); background: var(--ink); padding: .1em .4em; border-radius: 3px; }
    .tool-meta { display: flex; gap: .5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
    .badge { font-size: .7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .05em; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 3px; padding: .15rem .5rem; color: var(--rune); }
    .tool-cta { font-size: .78rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: .07em; color: var(--ember); }

    .closing { max-width: 780px; border-top: 1px solid var(--line); padding-top: 2.5rem; }
    .closing h2 { font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
    .closing p { color: var(--parchment-dim); line-height: 1.85; font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
    .closing p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .closing a { color: var(--ember); }
    .closing code { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: .84em; color: var(--rune); background: var(--ink); padding: .1em .4em; border-radius: 3px; }
  </style>
</Base>
